b'' b"several recent posts have identified the english word 'easter' with" b"the babylonian goddess 'ishtar'." b'' b"'easter' is a pagan word all right, but it has nothing to do with ishtar." b"if 'easter' and 'ishtar' were related, their history would show it." b"but in old english, easter was 'eostre', cognate with english 'east'" b"and german 'ost'. the reconstructed proto-germanic form is 'austron'." b"not until after did 'easter' have a high front vowel like 'ishtar'." b'clearly, the two words have quite separate origins.' b'' b'there may be neo-pagans who worship ishtar at easter, but if so, they' b'are making either a mistake of etymology, or a deliberate play on words.' b'' b'-- michael covington (ph.d., linguistics)' b'' b'' b'' b'--' b':- michael a. covington, associate research scientist b':- the university of georgia phone b':- athens, georgia u.s.a. amateur radio n4tmi 